<hl>
<seg id=1> Dole Appeals to World to Take Impotence Seriously In Advertisements for Viagra </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (ASSOCIATED PRESS WIRE New York) A Republican contender for president in 1996, Bob Dole is now representing the male strengthening drug Viagra, made by the Pfizer company, that is sweeping the world. He is alerting people to the seriousness of impotence. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Dole will talk about the importance of impotence and general male health in an educational television commercial </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Pfizer is unwilling to reveal how much money they are giving Dole. He will not mention the name Viagra in the commercial. </seg>
<seg id=5> The commercial will air at the beginning of next year. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Dole's commercial will be the first time Pfizer has marketed Viagra on television. </seg>
<seg id=7> Pfizer is considering whether or not to mention Viagra directly in future commercials. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In May of this year, Dole admitted to using Viagra, and was full of praise for it, calling it a "miracle drug". </seg>
<seg id=9> In his statement, the 75 year-old Dole said, "I believe these activities will help men to take seriously the health problems that they're afraid of talking about." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> American doctors have written more than six million prescriptions for the male strengthening drug since it on the market in April of this year,. </seg>
<seg id=11> The United States has 10 or 20 million men who are impotent. Among them, about ten percent seek treatment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Dole has been on a discussion program, and from his position in Congress has reminded citizens to diagnose prostate cancer early, and to be aware of its side effect - impotence. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Dole was diagnosed with prostate cancer in 1991, and after surgery the doctors said that he was okay. </seg>
</p>
